						<label.designator>15:92.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Plans for individuals with regular income—Conversion from Chapter 7 to Chapter 13 is tempered by good faith: <ital>Marrama v. Citizens Bank of Massachusetts</ital>[<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec30c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">1</footnote.reference>]<ital>U.S. v. Reorganized CF &amp; I Fabricators of Utah, Inc.</ital>[<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec30c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6b">2</footnote.reference>]</headtext>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<paratext>
						Any given.[<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec33c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">4</footnote.reference>] In this case <page no="971"/>and prebankruptcy transfers.
					</paratext>
				</para>
				<para>
					<paratext>The majority held that a patina of good faith overlayed the debtor&apos;s choice of Chapter.[
						<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec34c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">5</footnote.reference>] 
						Bankruptcy Code § 706(d)
					</paratext>
				</para>
				<para>
